This place is small, but it packs a punch!  I was able to try a few slices at this spot and I have to say the pizza had a great texture and flavor to it.  I really enjoy the concept here. The slice was crisp and delicious!  I also have had the pleasure of trying their L'Industrie and Burrata slices.  And wow, the Burrata cheese is SO on point!  I really liked having this topping on their pizza and it was a 100% win for me.  I recommend trying a slice that has Burrata in it for sure!  Like I mentioned, the place is small with barely any places to sit.  However on a nice day, you can sit outside! As a note, they have a minimum spend before you can use a credit card, so make sure you have some cash!

I came here with my family just as they were opening. The staff was as friendly and informative as I could have reasonably expected.  Their pizza was beyond my expectations though. I've had a few in New York at this point; their Papi pizza blew me away. It hit all the right notes for me. The garlic was clearly the melody, but there were layers of harmony behind it - was it the creme fraiche? The brie? Truffle sauce? I don't know, but it was delicious.  The texture was as good as I can imagine a pizza being - crispy crust that was satisfying to bite through and a gooey top that was just right - I do not know how to ask for anything better.  The ambiance was very cozy. There aren't many seats (I'm talking like 5 seats total), but the casual and laid back decor put us at ease while the food wow'd.

The New Yorker had a lot of flavor from the sausage and pepperoni and the prosciutto one had a lot of flavor from the truffle! It was great. Pizza crust is thin and not soggy at all, and it's quite chewy. I'm definitely a fan and will make it back here in time! Slices are huge too and they do sell by the slice, though it's cheaper (of course) to get an entire pie. It was quite well-priced for the entire pizza, and it was great, definitely recommend!

The guys running the place are very social media savvy and have corralled a LOT of friends to achieve their rating. Just go try it and see for yourself, or skip it and try the places I suggested. This place has the most genuine a warm staff.  The pizza the kind of pizza for pizza lovers and pizza snobs. The burrata is LIT! Massimo is a sweetheart. Everyone has to try this place. The vibe, the music, the food, and the people are all wonderful.

As an Long Island/New Yorker, this is honestly some of the best pizza I've ever had. They use a sourdough crust that's aged for three days and it really ties the slice together. Even their plain white slice is garnished w/ bakery style dollops of cream cheese and a basil leaf. Amazing pizza and a really cool staff. 100%
Authentic Italian pizza and one of my personal favorites. The restaurant area is small and cozy, but unfortunately is so small it lacks a bathroom. They also deliver and the staff is very friendly.
I was a bit disappointed with nyc pizzas, the fame is far from the taste, but this was in trully good, and worth the fame! really good pizza in a tiny and crowd local.
An absolute gem although unassuming. This is my favorite pizza place with its top quality ingredients. I love the burrata, but you truly can’t go wrong!

Let's get one thing straight, they have amazing pizza here. It's light, the crust is great and the toppings are fresh. You can easily go through two to three slices and not feel bad about it. It's very cozy so I hope you get a seat and eat it right there while it's hot.
Most underrated slice joint in NYC. Super nice folks here, incredible Pizza. There should be lines out the door.  Don't tell your friends, though

Id love to give this place a higher rating. The pizza is actually decent. But ive come on different occasions and the man goes from sitting on his laptop or his phone to making pizza without washing his hands. Do you know how many germs are on a phone. Just really grossed me out.
I tried the Fig & Goat Cheese and it is on another level. Highly recommend it! Ingredients are fresh af here too! I wanna give this spot 10 stars.

Although the fact that my close friend works here may result in some bias, the pizza does not fall short of being delicious. It's always hot, the cheese is always gooey, and the crust has the right amount of crunch. The combination of a homely, warm atmosphere and authentic pizza generates an experience like no other. I've never had a bad time here and I've certainly had more laughs here with friends and family than I can count. All in all, the warm pizza and the warm vibes earns L'industrie pizzeria a five star rating.

The guy at the counter was so welcoming the moment we walked in. As most places, he asked what we wanted, we told him and when we said we wanted to eat it, he said have a seat. And I mean, that’s nothing special per se, but it wasn’t like pay me first then eat, it was sit and relax. It was a very chill place to sit and eat. They have glass bottled sodas which seemed to be even better than canned sodas.  All that is second compared to the food. The pizza, The New Yorker, was amazing. The flavors were on point, the pizza was cooked very well and it wasn’t even burnt on the bottom. The toppings were plentiful and the ricotta was amazing. The employees were so nice. Definitely will visit them again when I come back to New York. Being a tourist and finding this place all the way in Brooklyn (from Manhattan only riding the subway) wasn’t easy, but well worth the trek.

Solid caramelized onions and brie and okay plain cheese slice. The first was $5 and the second $3. It's a tiny, cash only place and the pizza takes about 7-10 minutes to make/heat so not great if you're in a rush. If I could I would give it 3.5 stars, the price was just not worth the quality as the quality was only slightly above average.
